"{\"uid\": \"gbnews.com-sport-other-sport-olympics-derek-redmond-team-gb-target-golden-summer-athletes\", \"text\": \"Olympics: Derek Redmond has opened up ahead of the big event this summer  GETTY  ByJack Hayes,  Published: 23/07/2024  Updated: 24/07/2024  The 58-year-old has opened up ahead of the big event this summer  Athletics legend Derek Redmond is tipping Team GB to enjoy a golden Summer at the Paris Olympics.  The retired sprinter thinks Britain's sporting stars could even finish in the top three in the final medals table.  The retired sprinter's appearance in the Barcelona Games in 1992 remains one of the most iconic moments in Olympic history.Redmond, is now one of theofficial best motivational speakers- and travels the world to talk about his career.Olympics: Derek Redmond has opened up ahead of the big event this summer|GETTYBut the 58-year-old said that wherever he will be at the start of the Games he will be tuning in and cheering on Team GB.He said: \\\"I am really looking forward to it, Paris is a great city, and I think it will be a great backdrop for the games. I have no doubt the French will put on a good show.\\\"As for Team GB, I think we can look forward to a golden Summer. We are certainly one of the top four or five countries in the world. It would be great if we can get third or higher in the final table.\\\"Let us go for it. We seem to pull it out for the Olympics each year so I am expecting a lot, although I do not want to put too much pressure on them. But I would expect to be in the top five nations on that final medals table.\\\"JUST IN:Mike Tyson 'is in no fit state' as Jake Paul receives alternative offer after Mike Perry winOutlining who is most excited about seeing this Summer he said: \\\"I am looking forward to seeing Dina Asher-Smith and also the American Sha'Carri Richardson.\\\"Some people like her, some people do not like her. She's absolutely brilliant. I think she's great for the sport. She's a bit of a character. She can blow hot and cold performance-wise, but she pulled it out of the bag after a terrible semi-final of the World Championship where she ended up with lane nine and won the 100 metres final.\\\"I am a massive fan. She's like a modern day Florence Griffith Joyner, but just with a bit of energy and bite.\\\"So yeah, I am looking forward to seeing her because whatever she does, she will have people talking.\\\"READ MORE:Luke Littler shows off weight loss with fans blown away just days after Eloise Milburn splitAsked who he believes the greatest Olympian of all time is he said: \\\"The obvious one for me is Daley Thompson, because he's one of my all time heroes.\\\"Obviously a double Olympic champion, he held the world record at the time. So for me, I guess he would be the greatest but then I am also a massive Michael Jordan fan and he would be up there on that list.\\\"During his career, Redmond held the British record for the 400 metres sprint, and won gold medals in the 4x400 metres relay at the World Championships and European Championships.At the 1992 Olympic Games in Barcelona, he tore his hamstring in the 400 metres semi-final but continued the race limping and, with assistance from his father, managed to complete a full lap of the track as the crowd gave him a standing ovation.LATEST SPORTS NEWS:Andy Murray 'an inspiration' and 'wonderful role model' as tennis star confirms he will retire after OlympicsEngland could be about to shoot themselves in the foot with next manager search after Gareth Southgate exitBBC's highest-paid sports presenters revealed with Alex Scott paid more than John McEnroeOlympics: Derek Redmond has high hopes for Team GB this summer|PAThe incident has become a well-remembered moment in Olympic history, having been the subject of one of the International Olympic Committee's 'Celebrate Humanity' videos. It has been used in advertisements by Visa as an illustration of the Olympic spirit and featured in Nike's \\\"Courage\\\" commercials in 2008.President Obama even referenced it in one of his speeches.But asked about his favourite Olympic moment, Remond said: \\\"There is so many. Ironically, even though 1992 was the worst for me, it also provided a great memory - as the Dream Team came back to basketball.\\\"The American Dream Team doing what they did was pretty spectacular. It was like an exhibition watching those guys do what they do. That's way up there for me.Olympics: Derek Redmond thinks Dina Asher-Smith is one to watch this summer|PA\\\"But my most memorable, maybe for all the wrong reasons, was Ben Johnson and that 100 metres in 1988.\\\"That was my first Olympics and we were at the stadium watching. We were quite close to the finish line, quite low down so I had great views.\\\"I remember seeing that race and we were just dumbfounded with the performance and then obviously 24 hours later the news came out.\\\"That was definitely a situation that completely numbed certainly every athlete competing at the Olympic Games from whatever country you were. In the whole village, there was a numbness and a buzz around.\\\"For more information visit hiskeynote speakerspage.  The retired sprinter's appearance in the Barcelona Games in 1992 remains one of the most iconic moments in Olympic history.  Redmond, is now one of theofficial best motivational speakers- and travels the world to talk about his career.  Olympics: Derek Redmond has opened up ahead of the big event this summer  GETTY  But the 58-year-old said that wherever he will be at the start of the Games he will be tuning in and cheering on Team GB.  He said: \\\"I am really looking forward to it, Paris is a great city, and I think it will be a great backdrop for the games. I have no doubt the French will put on a good show.  \\\"As for Team GB, I think we can look forward to a golden Summer. We are certainly one of the top four or five countries in the world. It would be great if we can get third or higher in the final table.  \\\"Let us go for it. We seem to pull it out for the Olympics each year so I am expecting a lot, although I do not want to put too much pressure on them. But I would expect to be in the top five nations on that final medals table.\\\"  JUST IN:Mike Tyson 'is in no fit state' as Jake Paul receives alternative offer after Mike Perry win  Outlining who is most excited about seeing this Summer he said: \\\"I am looking forward to seeing Dina Asher-Smith and also the American Sha'Carri Richardson.  \\\"Some people like her, some people do not like her. She's absolutely brilliant. I think she's great for the sport. She's a bit of a character. She can blow hot and cold performance-wise, but she pulled it out of the bag after a terrible semi-final of the World Championship where she ended up with lane nine and won the 100 metres final.  \\\"I am a massive fan. She's like a modern day Florence Griffith Joyner, but just with a bit of energy and bite.  \\\"So yeah, I am looking forward to seeing her because whatever she does, she will have people talking.\\\"  READ MORE:Luke Littler shows off weight loss with fans blown away just days after Eloise Milburn split  Asked who he believes the greatest Olympian of all time is he said: \\\"The obvious one for me is Daley Thompson, because he's one of my all time heroes.  \\\"Obviously a double Olympic champion, he held the world record at the time. So for me, I guess he would be the greatest but then I am also a massive Michael Jordan fan and he would be up there on that list.\\\"  During his career, Redmond held the British record for the 400 metres sprint, and won gold medals in the 4x400 metres relay at the World Championships and European Championships.  At the 1992 Olympic Games in Barcelona, he tore his hamstring in the 400 metres semi-final but continued the race limping and, with assistance from his father, managed to complete a full lap of the track as the crowd gave him a standing ovation.  LATEST SPORTS NEWS:  Olympics: Derek Redmond has high hopes for Team GB this summer  PA  The incident has become a well-remembered moment in Olympic history, having been the subject of one of the International Olympic Committee's 'Celebrate Humanity' videos. It has been used in advertisements by Visa as an illustration of the Olympic spirit and featured in Nike's \\\"Courage\\\" commercials in 2008.  President Obama even referenced it in one of his speeches.  But asked about his favourite Olympic moment, Remond said: \\\"There is so many. Ironically, even though 1992 was the worst for me, it also provided a great memory - as the Dream Team came back to basketball.  \\\"The American Dream Team doing what they did was pretty spectacular. It was like an exhibition watching those guys do what they do. That's way up there for me.  Olympics: Derek Redmond thinks Dina Asher-Smith is one to watch this summer  PA  \\\"But my most memorable, maybe for all the wrong reasons, was Ben Johnson and that 100 metres in 1988.  \\\"That was my first Olympics and we were at the stadium watching. We were quite close to the finish line, quite low down so I had great views.  \\\"I remember seeing that race and we were just dumbfounded with the performance and then obviously 24 hours later the news came out.  \\\"That was definitely a situation that completely numbed certainly every athlete competing at the Olympic Games from whatever country you were. In the whole village, there was a numbness and a buzz around.\\\"  For more information visit hiskeynote speakerspage.  \"}"